%p.intro
  Every want's those coveted 'rich snippets' in their google search results. You know, the 
  ones with stars or the authors name beside them, but sh*t is complex.  
%P
  It's no secret that the click-through rate on those
  is astronomical, but after coming off of a recent e-commerce project, 
  I've learned that getting those snippets is not as easy at it looks. 
%p
  <strong>It's a crapshoot</strong>. Google says they support the schema.org markup format,
  but the current Google Structured Markup Tester doesn't show a preview of the search results. 
  Nore does google specify which schema.org definitions they support in their rich-snippets. 
  So to stay on the safe side, I use the depreciated data-vocabulary.org definitions, 
  which are well-documented and supported by Google. However, keep in mind that all this stuff will change in the future. 

%p
  So to give you a comprehensive idea of how rich-snippets work, I'm listing all the supported properties, followed by code examples as well as a link
  to a real example. Required properties are in <code class='required'>red</code>. Any page can be testes using the <a href="http://www.google.com/webmasters/tools/richsnippet">Google Structured Data Testing Tool</a>
  So I encourage you to use it. 

